{"test_cases_lookup_map": {"{\"actual_output\": \"The four primary stages of the Data Engineering lifecycle are:\\n\\n1. Ingestion\\n2. Transformation\\n3. Storage\\n4. Serving\\n\\nThese stages are the cornerstone of the data engineering lifecycle and are controlled by data engineers. They turn raw data into a useful end product, ready for consumption by analysts, data scientists, ML engineers, and others.\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"The four stages are Generation, Ingestion, Transformation, and Serving.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"What are the four primary stages of the Data Engineering lifecycle?\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"Data idempotency refers to the ability of a data pipeline or process to produce the same output given the same input, regardless of the number of times the process is repeated. In other words, if a data pipeline is idempotent, running it multiple times with the same input will always result in the same output, without any unintended side effects or changes to the data. This concept is important in data engineering because it ensures that data pipelines are reliable, predictable, and can be safely retried or repeated without causing data inconsistencies or errors.\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"It is the property where an operation can be applied multiple times without changing the result beyond the initial application.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"Define the concept of Data Idempotency in data pipelines.\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"The 'Transformation' stage in an ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) process is where the extracted data is converted into a format that is suitable for analysis or reporting. This stage can include various operations such as:\\n\\n1. Data cleaning: Removing duplicates, handling missing values, and correcting errors in the data.\\n2. Data aggregation: Combining data from multiple sources into a single dataset.\\n3. Data filtering: Selecting a subset of data based on specific conditions.\\n4. Data sorting: Arranging data in a specific order.\\n5. Data formatting: Converting data into a specific format, such as converting date formats or numeric formats.\\n6. Data mapping: Mapping data from one format to another, such as converting codes or categorizing data.\\n7. Data validation: Checking data for consistency and accuracy.\\n\\nThe transformation stage is critical in ensuring that the data is accurate, complete, and consistent, and that it meets the requirements of the target system. It also helps to improve the quality of the data and makes it more suitable for analysis or reporting.\\n\\nSome common transformation techniques used in ETL include:\\n\\n1. Data masking: Hiding sensitive data, such as credit card numbers or personal identifiable information.\\n2. Data encryption: Protecting data by converting it into a coded format.\\n3. Data compression: Reducing the size of the data to improve storage and transmission efficiency.\\n4. Data normalization: Organizing data into a standardized format to improve data integrity and reduce data redundancy.\\n\\nOverall, the transformation stage is a critical component of the ETL process, as it enables organizations to convert raw data into a usable and meaningful format that can be used to support business decision-making.\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"The stage where raw data is cleaned, filtered, and formatted for the target destination.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"Explain the 'Transformation' stage in an ETL process.\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"The difference between Batch and Stream processing is that Batch processing involves processing large chunks of data at once, whereas Stream processing involves processing data in real-time, as it is generated. Batch processing is suitable for handling large amounts of data that can be processed in a single batch, while Stream processing is ideal for applications that require immediate processing and analysis of data, such as live statistics and dashboards.\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"Batch processing handles large blocks of data at intervals, while Stream processing handles data in real-time as it arrives.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"What is the difference between Batch and Stream processing?\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"The three pillars of the CIA Triad in network security are:\\n\\n1. Confidentiality: This refers to the protection of sensitive information from unauthorized access, use, or disclosure.\\n2. Integrity: This refers to the accuracy, completeness, and consistency of data, as well as the prevention of unauthorized modification or deletion.\\n3. Availability: This refers to the ability of authorized users to access and use the information and systems they need, when they need them.\\n\\nThese three concepts form the foundation of information security and are often referred to as the CIA Triad.\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"Confidentiality, Integrity, and Availability.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"What are the three pillars of the CIA Triad in network security?\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"Asymmetric encryption differs from symmetric encryption in that it uses a pair of keys: a public key for encryption and a private key for decryption. This is in contrast to symmetric encryption, which uses the same secret key for both encryption and decryption. Asymmetric encryption is often used for secure communication over the internet, such as in online transactions and email encryption, due to its ability to provide authentication and non-repudiation. Symmetric encryption, on the other hand, is typically faster and more efficient, but requires a shared secret key between the parties involved.\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"Asymmetric uses a public key to encrypt and a private key to decrypt; Symmetric uses one shared key for both.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"How does Asymmetric Encryption differ from Symmetric Encryption?\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"The Domain Name System (DNS) is a system that translates human-readable domain names into IP addresses that computers can understand. It acts as a phonebook for the internet, allowing users to access websites and other online resources using easy-to-remember domain names instead of difficult-to-remember IP addresses. The main purpose of DNS is to provide a scalable and efficient way to manage the mapping of domain names to IP addresses, enabling users to access online resources easily and efficiently.\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"To translate human-readable domain names into IP addresses for networking.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"What is the purpose of the Domain Name System (DNS)?\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"A 'Port Scan' is a process used to identify open ports and services on a target system or network, typically as part of a security audit. It involves sending packets to a range of ports and analyzing the responses to determine which ports are open and listening. This information can be used to identify potential vulnerabilities and weaknesses in the system or network, and to inform the development of security measures to protect against potential threats. In the context of a security audit, a port scan can help to identify areas where the system or network may be exposed to attack, and to prioritize remediation efforts accordingly.\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"A method used to identify open ports on a server to discover potential services and vulnerabilities.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"Define a 'Port Scan' and its role in a security audit.\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"The primary goal of an Information Retrieval (IR) system is to find material (usually documents) of an unstructured nature (usually text) that satisfies an information need from within large collections (usually stored on computers).\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"To provide relevant documents to a user based on their specific information need.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"What is the primary goal of an Information Retrieval (IR) system?\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"Precision in IR evaluation is calculated as the fraction of the returned results that are relevant to the information need. It is defined as the number of true positives (relevant documents retrieved) divided by the total number of documents retrieved (true positives + false positives). The formula for precision is:\\n\\nPrecision = (Number of relevant documents retrieved) / (Total number of documents retrieved)\\n\\nFor example, if a search engine returns 10 documents, and 7 of them are relevant to the user's information need, the precision would be 7/10 or 0.7. This means that 70% of the documents returned by the search engine are relevant to the user's information need.\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"Precision is the fraction of retrieved documents that are actually relevant.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"How is Precision calculated in IR evaluation?\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"TF-IDF, or Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency, plays a crucial role in document ranking in information retrieval systems. It is a weighting scheme used to evaluate the importance of a term in a document based on its frequency of occurrence in the document and its rarity across the entire collection of documents.\\n\\nThe role of TF-IDF in document ranking can be summarized as follows:\\n\\n1. **Term Frequency (TF)**: TF measures the frequency of a term in a document. A higher TF score indicates that the term appears more frequently in the document.\\n2. **Inverse Document Frequency (IDF)**: IDF measures the rarity of a term across the entire collection of documents. A higher IDF score indicates that the term is less common across the collection.\\n3. **TF-IDF Weighting**: The TF-IDF weight of a term is the product of its TF and IDF scores. This weight represents the importance of the term in the document.\\n\\nThe TF-IDF weighting scheme has several effects on document ranking:\\n\\n* **Boosts rare terms**: TF-IDF gives more weight to rare terms, which are likely to be more important for distinguishing between documents.\\n* **Reduces common terms**: TF-IDF reduces the weight of common terms, which are less important for distinguishing between documents.\\n* **Improves document ranking**: By taking into account both the frequency of a term in a document and its rarity across the collection, TF-IDF improves the ranking of documents based on their relevance to a query.\\n\\nIn summary, TF-IDF is a crucial component of document ranking in information retrieval systems, as it helps to evaluate the importance of terms in a document and improves the ranking of documents based on their relevance to a query.\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"It weights terms to prioritize those frequent in a specific document but rare in the overall collection.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"What is the role of TF-IDF in document ranking?\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"The Vector Space Model (VSM) is a mathematical model used in information retrieval and natural language processing to represent documents and queries as vectors in a high-dimensional space. The model is based on the idea that documents and queries can be represented as points or vectors in a vector space, where each dimension corresponds to a term or word in the document or query.\\n\\nIn the VSM, each document is represented as a vector, where each component of the vector corresponds to the weight or importance of a particular term in the document. The weight of a term in a document is typically calculated using a term weighting scheme, such as term frequency-inverse document frequency (tf-idf), which takes into account the frequency of the term in the document and its rarity across the entire collection of documents.\\n\\nThe VSM has several key components:\\n\\n1. **Term space**: The set of all unique terms or words in the document collection.\\n2. **Document vectors**: Each document is represented as a vector, where each component corresponds to the weight of a term in the document.\\n3. **Query vectors**: Each query is represented as a vector, where each component corresponds to the weight of a term in the query.\\n4. **Similarity measure**: A measure of the similarity between two vectors, such as the dot product or cosine similarity, is used to calculate the similarity between documents and queries.\\n\\nThe VSM is used for a variety of tasks, including:\\n\\n1. **Document retrieval**: The VSM is used to rank documents in response to a query, based on their similarity to the query vector.\\n2. **Document classification**: The VSM is used to classify documents into categories, based on their similarity to a set of training documents.\\n3. **Document clustering**: The VSM is used to group similar documents together, based on their similarity to each other.\\n\\nThe VSM has several advantages, including:\\n\\n1. **Efficient computation**: The VSM allows for efficient computation of similarity between documents and queries, using vector operations such as dot products and matrix multiplications.\\n2. **Flexible weighting schemes**: The VSM allows for the use of different term weighting schemes, such as tf-idf, to capture the importance of terms in documents and queries.\\n3. **High-dimensional representation**: The VSM can represent documents and queries in a high-dimensional space, allowing for the capture of subtle relationships between terms and concepts.\\n\\nHowever, the VSM also has some limitations, including:\\n\\n1. **High dimensionality**: The VSM can suffer from the curse of dimensionality, where the number of dimensions is very large, making computation and storage of vectors challenging.\\n2. **Sparse vectors**: The VSM can result in sparse vectors, where most components are zero, making computation and storage of vectors challenging.\\n3. **Lack of semantic meaning**: The VSM represents documents and queries as vectors, but does not capture the semantic meaning of the terms and concepts, which can limit its effectiveness in certain applications.\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"A model where documents and queries are represented as vectors in a multi-dimensional space to calculate similarity.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"Explain the Vector Space Model.\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"It seems like you don't have any mastery scores yet. Let's work on some Information Retrieval concepts and then I can transfer you to the evaluator to assess your understanding. What topic would you like to explore in Information Retrieval?\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"The system should trigger the check_mastery_level tool for 'Information Retrieval'.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"What is my current mastery level in Information Retrieval?\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}, "{\"actual_output\": \"I'm happy to help you with your question, but I need to know your actual user ID to check your mastery level. Please provide me with your user ID so I can assist you further.\", \"context\": null, \"expected_output\": \"The system should trigger the check_mastery_level tool for 'Data Engineering'.\", \"hyperparameters\": null, \"input\": \"How many points do I have in Data Engineering?\", \"retrieval_context\": null}": {"cached_metrics_data": [{"metric_data": {"name": "Answer Relevancy", "threshold": 0.7, "success": false, "strictMode": false, "evaluationModel": "gpt-4-turbo", "evaluationCost": 0}, "metric_configuration": {"threshold": 0.7, "evaluation_model": "gpt-4-turbo", "strict_mode": false, "include_reason": true}}]}}}